{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539766"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16699"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16699"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.07,0.01,0.13,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1476"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"8874"},{"type":"tags","id":"8875"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22208"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive blurring of vision in her right eye. She also reports occasional flashes of light with something floating in her vision. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never had any previous eye problems, and has Fitzpatrick skin type 1. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/18 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Fundoscopy reveals a pigmented, dome-shaped elevated lesion in the superior temporal quadrant of the right eye. B-scan ultrasonography shows an acoustically hollow, dome-shaped lesion measuring 4 mm in height with associated subretinal fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retinal detachment","Age-related macular degeneration","Central retinal vein occlusion","Choroidal naevus","Choroidal melanoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Echoroidal melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E, including visual disturbance and a pigmented, elevated lesion on fundoscopy. The B-scan ultrasound findings of an acoustically hollow, dome-shaped lesion with subretinal fluid are characteristic of choroidal melanoma. Uveal melanomas (that is, of the iris ciliary body or choroid) are the most common primary intraocular cancer in adults, and they are typically aggressive with poor prognosis in later stages. Melanomas from the choroid is the most common of the uveal tract sites. Patients may present with blurry vision, decreased visual field loss, floaters, photopsia or be asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key features supporting choroidal melanoma in this case include the dome shape, height greater than 2 mm, presence of subretinal fluid, and acoustic hollowness on ultrasound. These findings warrant urgent referral to an ophthalmologist for further evaluation and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echoroidal naevus\u003C/strong\u003E is typically flat or minimally elevated (less than 2 mm in height), lacks subretinal fluid, and remains stable over time. The height of 4 mm in this case makes a naevus unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E presents with sudden painless vision loss and is characterised by retinal haemorrhages in all four quadrants, dilated tortuous veins, and cotton wool spots. It would not present with a dome-shaped mass lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge-related macular degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with central vision loss and involves the macula rather than the peripheral retina. The characteristic findings include drusen, geographic atrophy, or choroidal neovascularisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E may present with similar symptoms but would appear as an elevated, mobile retinal surface with a different appearance on B-scan ultrasound. While retinal detachment can be associated with choroidal melanoma, it would not explain the solid mass lesion seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Choroidal melanoma typically presents with visual disturbance, floaters, or may be asymptomatic.","B-scan ultrasonography showing a dome or mushroom-shaped lesion is characteristic of choroidal melanoma."],"references":["Soliman N, Mamdouh D, Elkordi A. Choroidal Melanoma: A Mini Review. Medicines (Basel). 2023.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9863301/","Shields C et al. Choroidal and Ciliary Body Melanoma.  American Academy of Ophthalmology EyeWiki. 2024.  Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Choroidal_and_Ciliary_Body_Melanoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16699"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T23:35:53+10:30","